name: sourdough
notes: |
  This recipe can be steered toward two different results. Each decision point below is
  tagged with the style it favours:

    (A) OPEN/ARTISAN  - thick crackly crust, chewy centre, big irregular air bubbles
    (B) EVEN/SPONGY   - thinner conventional crust, soft spongy crumb, small evenly-distributed
                        bubbles (cafe sandwich-sourdough style)

  The levers that separate them are: hydration, enrichment, how hard you degas at shaping, and
  how you bake (dutch oven + steam vs open / loaf tin). Pick one column and stay in it.
components:
  - name: starter maintenance
    ingredients:
      - item: filtered water
        mass: 18
      - item: flour
        mass: 30
      - item: starter
        mass: 12
    yield: makes 30g + 18g + 50g + 30g + 20-25g + 12g
  - name: mixing
    ingredients:
      - item: bread flour
        mass: 500
        basis: true
      - item: water
        mass: 350
        qty: 70
        unit: '%'
        note: '(A) 350g (70%) — wetter dough lets bubbles balloon into big holes; (B) 310-325g (62-65%) — stiffer dough holds many small uniform cells. 70% assumes 80:20 white:wholemeal; for (B) nudge toward more wholemeal / some all-purpose to soften gluten → finer crumb'
      - item: active stiff starter
        mass: 50
        qty: 10
        unit: '%'
      - item: salt
        mass: 10
      - item: oil or soft butter
        mass: 25
        optional: true
        note: (B) enrichment — biggest lever for soft/spongy, keeps it soft past day one. ~20-30g
      - item: milk
        optional: true
        note: (B) enrichment — swap 50-100g of the water above for milk
      - item: sugar or honey
        mass: 15
        optional: true
        note: (B) enrichment
      - item: instant yeast
        mass: 2.5
        optional: true
        note: '(B) optional pinch (~2-3g) — faster, more uniform rise & reliably even bubbles (closest to cafe sandwich sourdough). if used, fermentation is much faster — see timings'
    steps:
      - combine all ingredients in a bowl
      - wait 30 mins
      - step: do windowpane translucency test
        substeps:
          - if it tears, knead 2-3 mins, rest 10 mins, repeat
  - name: fermentation
    steps:
      - with wet hands, round the dough to make nice round surface
      - step: cover bowl and let dough rise, go based on criteria not the clock
        substeps:
          - 30% - 50% volume rise (use aliquot jar)
          - surface bubbles visible
          - jiggly texture when bowl shaken
          - sweet/sour smell
      - step: timing
        substeps:
          - 'sourdough only: 6-12 hrs'
          - '(B) + pinch of yeast: much faster, ~2-4 hrs — watch the criteria, it will run away from you if you go by the old timings'
      - step: optionally stretch and fold during fermentation
        substeps:
          - (A) builds strength for big open holes
          - (B) skip or keep gentle — you don't want a strong open structure
  - name: shaping
    notes: |
      This is the other big lever between the two styles.
        (A) GENTLE — preserve the gas you built: handle softly, don't press the air out.
        (B) DEGAS  — knock the air out for even crumb: press/flatten the dough out before folding,
                     popping the big bubbles, then roll up tight with no trapped pockets. A tight
                     gas-free roll is what gives the regular sponge.
    steps:
      - use batard (oval) or boulard (round)
      - sprinkle some flour over dough while still in bowl
      - flip dough from bowl onto bench (topside in bowl becomes bottomside on bench, since topside in bowl is slightly drier)
      - add some flour around edges of dough
      - (B) press the dough out flat here, knocking the big bubbles out
      - step: fold (sticky) now-topside over a few times, knocking excess flour off
        substeps:
          - right to middle
          - left to middle
          - top to middle
      - step: roll top to middle to yield a smooth topside
        substeps:
          - (B) roll firm and tight, no air gaps
      - add some flour on top
      - flip into banneton
      - '(B) alt: loaf tin instead of banneton — a tin bake (see baking B) is the easiest path to an even crumb + conventional sandwich crust'
  - name: proofing
    steps:
      - step: cover and refrigerate 8-96 hours to proof, or proof at room temp for 1-3 hours
        substeps:
          - (B) + pinch of yeast — room-temp proof only, ~1-1.5 hrs, until puffy
  - name: baking (A) — dutch oven + steam (thick crackly artisan crust)
    steps:
      - set oven to 230°C with dutch oven inside and preheat for 30 mins
      - score & spritz loaf, optionally add rice flour
      - bake 30 mins with dutch oven lid on (trapped steam = thick crust)
      - bake until desired crust colour / until internal temp reaches 92°C (20 more mins) with lid off
  - name: baking (B) — open bake (thinner soft conventional crust)
    steps:
      - set oven to 200-210°C conventional (no fan — fan dries & crisps the crust; drop ~20°C if you must use fan). no dutch oven, no steam — steam is what makes the thick crackly crust, so skip it here
      - score the loaf
      - bake on a tray (or in the loaf tin) until golden / internal 92°C, ~40-45 mins total
      - immediately out of the oven, while still hot, brush the top with milk or melted butter for a soft even golden crust — residual heat lets it soak in and steams the crust soft (don't brush before/during the bake; that firms the crust)
